# =============================================================================
# .gitignore — cuda-cpp-robotics-projects
#
# Like everything in this repo, this file is a teaching surface (CLAUDE.md §6):
# each rule explains WHY it exists. Git ignores anything matching these
# patterns; a leading `**/` makes a pattern match at any depth, which matters
# here because 505 project folders each produce their own build artifacts.
#
# Guiding rule (CLAUDE.md §8): commit SOURCES and TINY SAMPLES, never build
# outputs, downloaded datasets, or secrets. Everything ignored here must be
# reproducible by anyone from what IS committed (build it, or run the
# download/synthesis scripts).
# =============================================================================

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Visual Studio state (machine-local, regenerated automatically)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .vs/ holds VS's per-machine caches (IntelliSense DBs, window layout). It can
# grow to gigabytes and is meaningless on any other machine.
.vs/

# Per-user project settings (debugger args, startup project). These encode one
# person's local preferences, not the project itself.
*.vcxproj.user

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Build outputs (C++/CUDA)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Our .vcxproj files place all outputs under build/x64/<Config>/ inside each
# project. MSBuild also creates x64/ intermediate dirs next to project files.
# `**/x64/` catches both, in every one of the 505 project folders.
**/x64/

# Individual artifact types, wherever they land. Every one of these is
# regenerated by a build, so committing them would only bloat history.
# (NOTE: git does NOT support inline comments after a pattern — a trailing
# "# ..." becomes part of the pattern and silently disables it. Comments in
# this file therefore always sit on their own line, above the pattern.)
# In order: compiled objects (host+device), built demo exes (anyone rebuilds
# from source), debug symbol DBs, incremental-link state, linker exports,
# incremental-link object/symbol caches, build/run logs, MSBuild tracker logs.
*.obj
*.exe
*.pdb
*.ilk
*.exp
*.iobj
*.ipdb
*.log
*.tlog

# Optional CMake builds (the VS solution is the required path; CMake is a
# bonus for Linux learners — its build trees are throwaway):
cmake-build*/
out/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Python (used by scripts/make_synthetic.py and tools/)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CPython bytecode caches, stray compiled bytecode, and local virtual
# environments (recreate with `python -m venv`).
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.venv/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Data (CLAUDE.md §8: tiny committed samples YES, downloads NO)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Download scripts fetch public datasets into data/downloaded/ inside each
# project. Those can be large and often carry licenses that FORBID
# redistribution (e.g., KITTI, nuScenes) — they must never enter git history.
# The committed sample lives in data/sample/, which is NOT ignored: demos must
# run offline with zero downloads.
**/data/downloaded/

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OS junk
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Windows Explorer thumbnail cache and macOS Finder metadata (for anyone
# browsing a clone on a Mac).
Thumbs.db
.DS_Store

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Secrets (CLAUDE.md §7/§12: never commit secrets — no exceptions)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Environment files with tokens/keys, and private keys / certificates.
.env
*.pem

# =============================================================================
# Deliberately NOT ignored (so nobody "helpfully" adds rules for these later):
#   catalog.json               — generated, but load-bearing: agents and tools
#                                read it instead of re-parsing the catalog .md
#   **/data/sample/            — the tiny committed samples that make every
#                                demo run offline (reproducibility is sacred)
#   push-notes/                — the didactic record of every push (§7.1)
#   **/demo/expected_output.txt — the correctness oracle each demo is checked
#                                against by tools/verify_project.py
# =============================================================================
